primary_purpose: To serve as an interactive "table of contents" for a radio show being re-released in installments on Soundcloud. I'm not sure how much time I will personally be able to devote to tracking down anecdotes.
sets_apart_from_similar: I'm not sure there are other similar wikis.  This music group, while perhaps the most successful Western act of the past 30+ years, is not widely known, and its fan base is older, thus less internet savvy.  The information readily available about them on the internet is repetitive and sparse.  This wiki is not seeking to document their entire career, but rather is interested in making the radio episodes more easily navigable both for fans of the group and for those potentially looking for alternate recordings of Western classics.

primary_purpose: It would mainly be a place for curious film goers to confirm their speculations, discover facts, and get their questions answered. And then maybe a community where watchers like me, who are more interested in the social themes of the film, could discuss their opinions with other individuals.
sets_apart_from_similar: Well, it's very specific to one film series.
other_founders: I didn't start it with anyone
influence_list: There is already an audience here,Other (please explain)
influence-Other_text: As from what I understood, Wikia is writted most ly by fans (hence their tagline). And I simply believe that fans who could be quite obsessive, will be able to provide more accurate information to the Wikia.
primary_topic: A specific entertainment topic (musician, television show, book series, video game, etc.)
topic_expert: I know about as much as most people about the topic
composition_preference: 20 knowledgeable participants who care a lot about your topic
Why_popularity_level:
The film series by itself MAYBE has an average amount of fans (the films are mainstream, although they were met with mixed reviews). On the other hand, it is a horror film, and a good number of people love watching horror films.

Taking these into consideration, plus the fact that not everyone who is both a Purge and horror fan would take the time to write an article online, I would say that ten people would be a fair number of contributors when the Wikia reaches thirty days old.

why_start_wiki: I thought to myself, "Wow, I would love to fight Congress. Like the whole building. Everyone in it. Mano e mano. Winner takes all." But I realized I really didn't know much about our representatives weight class and fighting techniques. Only a fool walks into a fight blind. So I started to do some research on it, googling "how to fight your local representative wikihow" and "boxing vs gouging which most effective against 1%" Turns out, I'm one of the first to seriously ask these questions, much less have the answers. I'm a humanitarian at heart, so I took it upon myself to collect and put together all the fight stats on Congress, so that anyone looking to fight their local rep (or the whole Capitol -- we don't think small here) can have the edge they need to come out on top.
primary_purpose: To collect, curate, and centralize all known and theorized data on the martial capabilities of all past and present U.S. Congressman. Not martial as in like battle strategy, but as in "If I and Representative Nancy Pelosi (D-CA) got in a bar fight, who would win?" sort of thing. I may branch out to other branches of government after my work in the legislative branch is done.
sets_apart_from_similar: While we strive for accuracy, on a topic like this you have to allow for some amount of conjecture. Few current congressman are going to advertise any sort of history in fighting or violence; that's not how you get elected. So what really sets this wiki apart from others is we allow editors to put in a bit of the subjective into their work. There is room for deep analysis on this wiki and also for disagreement.

influence-Other_text: This is a scholarly endeavor, and that's what wikis are for. Scholarly endeavors.

topic_expert: I know more than most people about the topic

why_start_wiki:
Over the course of my life, I’ve embraced a number of different hobbies: baseball cards, video games, tennis, art, just to name a few. But none of them have changed my life or brought me as much satisfaction as blogging. In almost too many ways to count, it has changed me and the way I live my life.

In fact, so much so, it has become a hobby I regularly recommend to others. I started blogging as a personal tool to journal the changes we were making as we began minimizing our possessions. But somewhere along the line, it became less about me writing the story and more about the story changing me.

And while there are many articles written about why you should blog to grow your business or become an expert or make a whole bunch of money—the best recommendations are still found in the personal realization that blogging changes you, the writer.

why_start_wiki:
While working on my PhD, there was no *one-stop-shop* for all necessary info and skills for other people working in my field. People are somehow expected to soak up little tips and tricks by osmosis and it simply wasn't a very clever way of going about things. This is my attempt to collect all the 'tribal' knowledge I've collected over 4 years in the field. Hopefully, people who are looking for help will stumble across it.

At my new job, I'm working on compiling a training manual for all new engineers who, have a background in electronics, but who haven't had any exposure to the niche field that is antenna design and building for MRI.

why_start_wiki:
I like the Wikia format very much, in spite of not agreeing with everything they implement.  Meh, that's Life.  But to answer your question thoroughly, let's backtrack a bit.  

I started contributing to Wikia on an occasional basis back in 2012.  As a creative writer, I've written fanfiction and original pieces.  Wikia offers a writer a chance to express themselves in a big way with "articles."  I didn't become a regular contributor until I discovered one particular fandom that I write for and whose Wikia had gone stale and abused by trolls.  This made me angry, so I started to edit big time and when I asked the admin if she needed help, she made me co-admin.  From there I simply waited until another fandom resonated deeply with me enough to write fanfiction and discovered that Wikia had also lost its admin and was growing stale.  So, at that point, having admin experience, I followed the necessary "adoption" steps and took over as admin there.  Same with my third wikia.

I thought that was it until I viewed a film and read a manga series that blew me away.  I went looking for the Wikia and what?  No Wikia?  Can't be.  But yes, it was true and that's what drove me to start this one as a Founder.
primary_purpose: The parent company always stresses that the admins of a site are not The Emperor of China, but we're certainly more than what they claim we are which is "the mop and bucket crew."  Sorry, but if that's all the job entails, I don't want it.  A good admin knows they can't work alone and needs to have decent people skills and be able to communicate with others their "vision."  Every great admin has one and like a ship's captain, keeps steering the wikia towards that destination.  Adjustments are made along the way, but seriously, the best wikias are well-organized, well-written, and thorough in their knowledge of their topic (or on their way to being that expert).  Small wikias can be handled by one or two admins; but large wikias often have many admins.  I like the smaller ones or the ones not so busy that there are too many chefs (if you know what I mean).  It's a group project but every group in existence needs a leader, a go-to, a planner.  That's what I am for the wikias I administer (at least, I hope so).
motivation-Other_text: The chance to learn new skills by building a wiki "from scratch."
sets_apart_from_similar: It is the first Wikia of which I am aware dedicated to a specific film, its media, its creator and its characters.  It may even be the first Wikia to dedicated to the general topic.  I searched and haven't found anything similar.
other_founders: Other (please explain)
other_founders_other_text: I asked two online friends who are also fanfiction writers in the genre if they could help out.  They might, but I decided to go ahead and get started anyway.

why_start_wiki:
I like the idea of pitting fictional characters against each other, and like the idea of there being a dedicated site for people to share their ideas on that subject, and to do so as they envision- while being in a setting that encourages reason and respect.

There is already the Death Battle Fanon wiki. However, it strictly adheres to the parameters of an internet show called Death Battle- parameters I find limiting and unnecessary. People have been imagining who would beat who in a clash of worlds since well before the internet; there's no need to constrain oneself to one particular show's format, in my opinion.
primary_purpose: Providing a place where people can create and share their ideas of a crossover encounter with freedom.
sets_apart_from_similar:
On my wiki, the rules are different. Victory is not determined exclusively through death; characters can win without killing each other, although death will still be an option. Characters will also be *in-character*- something that Death Battle's rules waive away in favor of senseless bloodshed. Certain characters simply cannot be separated from their mercy, in my opinion, and it bothers me that Death Battle did so.

Also, I want a place where there is less vehemence. Death Battle and its fan-wiki seem to breed a lot of discontent.
other_founders: I didn't start it with anyone
influence_list: Other (please explain)
influence-Other_text: Wikia seems a more sound tool for creating an objective, intellectual environment for this subject. Facebook and Reddit, not so much.
primary_topic: Other (please explain)
primary_topic_other_text: Hypothetical encounters between different characters, hostile or otherwise.
topic_expert: I know less than most people about the topic
audience_size: Very niche - only a handful of people
composition_preference: 20 knowledgeable participants who care a lot about your topic
successful-Other_text: Coherent, interesting, informative, magnanimous, and engaging information about characters, presentations of the fights, and discussions about the hypothetical encounters in question.
Why_popularity_level: Well, to start with, almost everything I do is ignored by the majority, so I highly doubt anyone will find this wiki. Even if they do, I'm sure that they'll take at most one look at it and back away.
failure_list: If there is very little content on my community,There is no outcome that I would consider failure,Other (please explain)
failure-Other_text: I am honestly not sure what the parameters for failure would be. I must admit, despite my acceptance that almost no one shall find this thing, I still fantasize about a few select individuals participating, and doing so on multiple occasions. I also won't deny that I do wish to create a list of profiles for prospective characters, and perhaps to even create several matchups of my own imagining. So, in the face of this uncertainty, I suppose I'll have to select "All of the Above". I'd certainly be lying if I were to select the third option, and claim to be boldly certain in doing so.

why_start_wiki: OpenToonz is a free, open-source 2D animation program that recently came out. It's great, but it's confusing and hard to learn, and the original manual is in Japanese, so figuring it out has been a community-wide process of trial and error. I already used Wikia semi-regularly just to look things up and make the occasional minor edit, but I decided to found this wiki to organize the information the newly-made OpenToonz community was discovering.
primary_purpose: To act as a centralized database of knowledge on the essential functions of OpenToonz as a program. My goal is for all unfamiliar terms to be defined on the wiki and explained in relation to one another, so that an absolute beginner who stumbles upon it will be able to understand the basics without puzzling through a dozen outdated Youtube tutorials.
sets_apart_from_similar: This is the only one for OpenToonz, although I recently learned that there is a very small, inactive wiki for other Toonz products.
other_founders: I didn't start it with anyone
influence_list: Other (please explain)
influence-Other_text: There was already a FB group, subreddit, G+ group, etc. but no wiki. I want to supplement the other communities, not compete with them.
